  "prompt": "What if a cricket ball hits a batsman\u2019s helmet and then goes to the boundary?",
  "response": "In cricket, if a ball hits the batsman's helmet and then goes to the boundary, specific rules apply depending on the context:\n\n1. **Runs for Hit by Helmet:** If the batsman is wearing the helmet and the ball hits the helmet on the batsman's head or is being carried, runs are not awarded directly for the helmet hit itself. However, if the batsman has struck the ball personally (with the bat, hand holding the bat, or body) and it then deflects off the helmet, any runs completed or boundaries achieved are counted.\n\n2. **Boundary Scored:** If the ball deflects off the helmet (being worn) or from any part of the batsman's body after playing the ball with the bat, and it reaches the boundary, it is counted as runs. If it goes directly off the helmet (provided part of the batsman's equipment) to the boundary after being played by the batsman, four runs are awarded.\n\n3. **Interruption:** No runs are awarded if the ball directly hits a helmet (or any equipment) that is lying on the ground (typically this would be fielding side's equipment). This would result in dead ball.\n\nFor a precise interpretation, cricket regulations or playing conditions set by the authority governing the match like ICC or national boards must be referred to.",
